on’s life to the next, the author investigates how various McIlwraiths, both men and women, articulated their identity as subjects of the British Empire over time. Eva-Marie Kröller identifies parallel and competing forms of communication that involved major public figures beyond the family’s immediate circle, and explores the challenges issued by Indigenous people to imperial ideologies. Drawing from private papers and public archives, Writing the Empire is an illuminating biography that will appeal to readers interested in the links between life writing and imperial history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy20th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh  aAustralia.  aBritish Empire.  aCambridge.  aCanada.  aCanadians in World War One.  aIndigenous peoples.  aMcIlwraith.  aanthropology.  acolonialism.  afamily biography.  aimmigration.  aimperialism.  alife writing.  aornithology.  apost-WWI.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073922040uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753651040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487536510423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487536510/original  a978-3-11-073922-0  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aGBV-deGruyter-alles